'''Thore Albert Boye''' (27 October 1912 – 1 October 1999) was a Norwegian diplomat.

He was born in [[Oslo|Kristiania]] as a son of Supreme Court Justice [[Thorvald Boye]] (1871–1943) and Mia Esmarch (1880–1966). In 1945 he married Nøste Siem (1918–1999), a daughter of [[Ole Siem]] and sister of [[Martin Siem]].<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=Thore Boye|encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Kåre|last=Dæhlen|authorlink=Kåre Dæhlen|editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Thore_Boye/utdypning|language=Norwegian|accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref>

He took the [[cand.jur.]] degree in 1936, and was an attorney and deputy judge in [[Tromsø]] before being hired in the [[Norwegian Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] in 1938. After the Second World War reached Norway on 9 April 1940, and the government fled the capital, Boye set out on [[ski]]s to catch up with them. After doing so he acted as a courier to Stockholm, returned to Molde where he followed the [[flight of the Norwegian National Treasury]] to [[Tromsø]]. From Tromsø, he left the country together with the government and [[Norwegian royal family|royal family]]. They reached London, where Boye became a secretary in the [[Ministry of Finance (Norway)|Ministry of Finance]]-in-exile; from 1941 the [[Ministry of Defence (Norway)|Ministry of Defence]]-in-exile.<ref name=nbl/> He was promoted to assistant secretary in 1942.<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=Thore Albert Boye|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|editor=|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/Thore_Albert_Boye|language=Norwegian|accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> From 1944 he participated in the rebuilding after the [[liberation of Northern Norway]], and in the spring of 1945 he was a secretary for the provisional government in Oslo, awaiting the return of the real government from exile after the war.<ref name=nbl/>

He was a legation concellor in [[Belgium]] from 1946 to 1948, assistant secretary in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs from 1948 to 1949, secretary-general for the Northern European group in [[NATO]] from 1949 to 1951. He was promoted to sub-director in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs in 1951 and deputy under-secretary of state in 1953. From 1955 to 1961 he worked as vice chief executive in the [[SAS Group]],<ref name=nbl/> and he served as the Norwegian ambassador to [[Italy]] from 1961 to 1965. From 1962 he doubled as the ambassador to [[Greece]]. He was then the permanent under-secretary of state (the highest-ranking civil position) in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs from 1965 to 1971, then the Norwegian ambassador to [[Spain]] from 1972 to 1977 and [[Sweden]] from 1977 to 1981.<ref name=snl/>

He was decorated as a Commander with Star of the [[Order of St. Olav]] in 1969.<ref>{{cite book|last=Torgersen|first=Rolf Normann|authorlink=Rolf Normann Torgersen|title=Ordener|year=1987|publisher=Nye Atheneum|location=Oslo|language=Norwegian|isbn=82-7334-148-8|page=188}}</ref>

